value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: ent-cassa-12,15-diene + O2 + NADPH + H+ = ent-11beta-hydroxycassa-12,15-diene + NADP+ + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: 10beta-hydroxytaxa-4(20),11-dien-5alpha-yl acetate + O2 + NADPH + H+ = 10beta,14beta-dihydroxytaxa-4(20),11-dien-5alpha-yl acetate + NADP+ + H2O.

Catalysis of the reaction: abieta-7,13-dien-18-ol + NADPH + H+ + O2 = abieta-7,13-dien-18-al + NADP+ + 2 H2O. This is a two step reaction. The first step is: abieta-7,13-dien-18-ol + NADPH + H+ + O2 = abieta-7,13-dien-18,18-diol + + NADP+ + H2O. The second step is a spontaneous reaction: abieta-7,13-dien-18,18-diol = abieta-7,13-dien-18-al + H2O.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a histone protein by individual cells.

definition.value: This term was created even though it describes a process relating to a group of gene products, because histones are highly conserved proteins that are essential components of cellular chromatin in eukaryotic cells.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: 9beta-pimara-7,15-diene + 3 O2 + 3 reduced [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase] = 9beta-pimara-7,15-dien-19-oate + 4 H+ + 4 H2O + 3 oxidized [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase].

The covalent alteration of one or more amino acids occurring in proteins, peptides and nascent polypeptides (co-translational, post-translational modifications). Includes the modification of charged tRNAs that are destined to occur in a protein (pre-translation modification).
The process of an actomyosin ring getting smaller in diameter.

definition.value: This term can be used to annotate contraction of either bacterial or fungal contractile rings.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stem cell factor (SCF) stimulus.

label.value: cellular response to stem cell factor stimulus

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stem cell factor (SCF) stimulus.
Catalysis of the reaction: dGTP + H2O = dGMP + H+ + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: dTTP + H2O = dTMP + H+ + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: GTP + H2O = GMP + H+ + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: ITP + H2O = IMP + H+ + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: UTP + H2O = UMP + H+ + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: XTP + H2O = XMP + H+ + diphosphate.

definition.value: While XTP is not produced by cells, deamination of purine bases can result in accumulation of such nucleotides as ITP, dITP, XTP, and dXTP. XTPase contributes to the removal of these abnormal bases from the cellular pool of nucleotide triphosphates.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of adenine.

A special chromosome region located towards one end of a chromosome that contains dispersed copies of short, repetitive DNA sequences and functions as a cis-acting element essential for presynaptic homologous chromosome pairing and chromosome-nuclear envelope attachment.

label.value: cellular response to vitamin B1 starvation

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of vitamin B1 (also called thiamin and thiamine).

label.value: mitotic G2 cell cycle arrest in response to glucose starvation

value.value: The process in which the mitotic cell cycle is halted during G2 phase as a result of deprivation of glucose.

label.value: protein localization to nuclear inner membrane

value.value: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the nuclear inner membrane.
The change in morphology and behavior of a granulocyte resulting from exposure to a cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor.
The removal of glucuronic acid from a conjugated substrate.
The removal of glucuronic acid from an acyl-glucuronide.
The modification of an substrate by the conjugation of glucuronic acid to form an acyl-glucuronide (also called an acyl-glucuronoside).
Catalysis of the reaction: an acyl-glucuronoside + H2O = an alcohol + D-glucuronate.
Catalysis of the reaction: gallate + O2 = (1E)-4-oxobut-1-ene-1,2,4-tricarboxylate.

Catalysis of the reaction: taxusin + [reduced NADPH-hemoprotein reductase] + O2 = 7beta-hydroxytaxusin + [oxidized NADPH-hemoprotein reductase] + H2O. Also converts 2alpha-hydroxytaxusin to 2alpha,7beta-dihydroxytaxusin.
The region between the plasma membrane and the cell wall, as found in organisms such as filamentous fungi.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glutamate into 4-hydroxybutyrate.

definition.value: In the catabolism of glutamate in mammals, succinate semialdehyde is converted to succinate (see GO:0006540). Plants can utilize an alternative route, converting succinic semialdehyde to 4-hydroxybutyrate using gamma-hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: succinate semialdehyde + NADP+ + H2O = succinate + NADPH + 2 H+.

definition.value: This function is similar to EC:1.2.1.24 [succinate-semialdehyde dehydrogenase (NAD+)], and EC:1.2.1.16 [succinate-semialdehyde dehydrogenase (NAD(P)+)], but is specific for NADP+.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a neutral pH (pH close to 7) stimulus. pH is a measure of the acidity or basicity of an aqueous solution.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a menadione stimulus. Menadione (also called vitamin K3) is a naphthoquinone having a methyl substituent at the 2-position.

The directed movement of phytochelatin 2 (PC2) into the vacuole. Phytochelatin 2 is a glutathione-related peptide composed of (gamma-Glu-Cys)n-Gly where n=2, and where the Glu and Cys residues are linked through a gamma-carboxylamide bond.

The directed movement of phytochelatin 3 (PC3) into the vacuole. Phytochelatin 3 is a glutathione-related peptide composed of (gamma-Glu-Cys)n-Gly where n=3, and where the Glu and Cys residues are linked through a gamma-carboxylamide bond.

The directed movement of phytochelatin 4 (PC4) into the vacuole. Phytochelatin 4 is a glutathione-related peptide composed of (gamma-Glu-Cys)n-Gly where n=4, and where the Glu and Cys residues are linked through a gamma-carboxylamide bond.
The directed movement of cadmium ions into the vacuole.
The directed movement of a peroxisome along a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a methylamine stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a methylamine stimulus.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a multivesicular body. A multivesicular body is a type of late endosome in which regions of the limiting endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the cytoplasm.

The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a multivesicular body, a type of late endosome in which regions of the limiting endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the cytoplasm.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of raffinose that occur in the presence of oxygen.

The sequence of enzymatic reactions by which a cap structure is added to the 5' end of nascent RNA polymerase transcripts. Examples of RNA capping include 7-methyl-G caps found on all RNA polymerase II transcripts and nucleotide-containing cofactor caps, such as NAD(H) or FAD, found on bacterial trancripts.

Hypermethylation of the 7-(mono)methylguanosine (m(7)G) cap structure at the 2' position of the guanosine residue to convert a mono-methylated cap to a 2,2,7-trimethylguanosine cap structure. This type of cap modification occurs on small nuclear RNAs (snRNAs) and small nucleolar RNAs (snoRNAs) and is dependent on prior guanine-N7 methylation.
The appearance of granulysin due to biosynthesis or secretion following a cellular stimulus, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select one of the 'regulation' children terms.

value.value: The addition of a methyl group to the N7 atom in the base portion of a guanine nucleotide residue in an RNA molecule.

A multiprotein ATPase complex involved in the release of polyubiquitinated proteins, including those damaged by oxidative stress, from the outer mitochondria membrane into the cytoplasm where they are presented to the proteasome for proteolysis, a process also referred to as mitochondria-associated degradation (MAD). In budding yeast, this complex includes Cdc48p, Npl4p and Vms1p.
The growth of colonies in filamentous chains of cells into a substrate.
Self-propelled movement of an organism from one location to another through water, often by means of active fin movement.

definition.value: For behavioral aspects of swimming, consider instead annotating to 'swimming behavior ; GO:0036269'.

value.value: The response to external or internal stimuli that results in the locomotory process of swimming. Swimming is the self-propelled movement of an organism through the water.
